Node Express

  What is a port? Each port on a server is identified by a unique number
    Windows - netstat command to write in the terminal to check which port is listening
    netstat -ano | findstr "LISTENING"

Request Vocab for HTTP requests

  GET     - Request a resource from server (HTML website, piece of text, piece of data)
  POST    - Sending a resource to server (information, form/email/password)
  PUT     - Update method - Replace a resource with something
  PATCH   - Update method - Patch a resource
  DELETE  - Deletes a resource

Example:
  
  import express from "express";
  const app = express();
  
  app.get("/", (req, res) => {
    res.send("Hello, World!");
  });
  
  app.listen(3000, () => {
    console.log("Server running on port 3000.");
  });

Example 2:

  import express from "express";
  const app = express();
  const port = 3000;
  
  app.get("/", (req, res) => {
      res.send("<h1>hello world</h1><p>welcome to my page</p>");
  })
  
  app.get("/about", (req, res) => {
      res.send("<h1>About me</h1><p> my name is hani banani</p>");
  })
  
  app.get("/contact", (req, res) => {
      res.send("<h1>Contact me here:</h1><p>email@email.com</p>");
  })
  
  app.listen(port, () => {
      console.log(`Server has started on port ${port}`);
  });
  
